4.1.2 Electronics domain specific capabilities


     		Extensions to the generic capabilities for the electronics domain are provided. Due to the general nature of electronics, these options are considered applicable at higher levels
     		of product structure as determined by application implementation.


     		An interconnect may be embedded in a molded or composite product, as in an automobile dashboard that is an electrotechnical assembly containing several daughterboards connected
     		by flexible interconnect.


4.1.2.1 Network based design and analysis


     		Specific product structure options are provided to support network based design and analysis. Typical applications include block diagram or circuit design and analysis, with
     		functionality provided to directly support commonly understood industrial usage with externally defined  templates
     		using languages such as Spice(TM), C(TM), VHDL-AMS(TM), SystemC(TM), Verilog(TM), or Modelica(TM). The networks may be used to represent either lumped or
     		distributed systems depending on the approximations in the templates and the structural representation actually
     		selected during design or analysis. The externally defined simulation template is explicitly attached to the interface of elements in the network.
     		The networks obviously are not limited to electrical domain.



     		Once the functional network is accepted, physical components are selected,
     		a process known as packaging traverses the functional hierarchy with the result that each element of the network is related to the component that implements that element.
     		The mapping of the functional element to the physical component may be exchanged using this part
     		of ISO 10303, as supported by the Functional decomposition to design arm.  The ability of the mapping to be supported allows
     		formal traceability to be supported between functional and physical domains supporting dynamic back annotation.
     		The mapping results are explicitly represented by a flattened network representation of the connections between the physical components that are to be implemented by interconnect.

     	The network based design and analysis conformance options are:



     			Electrical network model;




     			Functional network interface model;



     			Functional network model;



     			Physical network topology model;



     			Requirement allocation to functional network element;



     			Simulation model template definition and application;



     			System wiring definition;



     			Thermal network model.






4.1.2.2 Requirements


Specific product structure options are provided to support requirements exchange, with extensive predefined classification provided.
     		A complete capability is provided to assign quantities to a requirement.
     		Requirements may be assigned to products, versions of products, product views and domain specific structures in those views.
     		The results of evaluating a design against requirements, including Design Rules, may be captured.
     		The results may include data tables, externally defined graphical representations or externally defined audio or visual representations.
     		Traceability is provided by supporting formal assignment between a node in the requirement decomposition tree and the element in the functional or physical design that is there to satisfy that requirement.
     		Traceability is also supported by supporting formal assignment between a node in the requirement decomposition tree and a class to which the element in the functional or physical design may be assigned, thus asserting that any element that is a member of that class is there to satisfy that requirement.
     		The generic requirement related conformance options are:




     			Requirement;



     			Planned and evaluated characteristics.




	Specific application of requirements are identified in other sections of this clause.


4.1.2.3 Rules
     	Design Rules may be managed with a complete life cycle and exchanged with an explicit representation language. The generic rules related conformance options are:



     			Rules;



     			Software.




4.1.2.4 Software
     	The software related conformance options are:



     			Software.






4.1.2.5 Packaging



  	Support is provided for both the assignment of mapping between the functional netlist and the assembly structure and the assignment of mapping between
  	the functional netlist and the interconnect structure.  Full support is provided for formally modeling the
  	multi-product physical assembly needed to actually implement the detailed functional netlist.  There is no
  	limitation imposed due to assuming there is only one CAD layout application being used to implement the physical
  	design.  The physical design may be split amongst three dimensional system for complex shapes, including the usage of
  	cables, and their connectors, and the two dimensional CAD system traditionally used for PWB board layout.
  	There is full traceability possible through the various model instances that represent the electro-mechanical design.  Principal
  	features of this apprach include strong support for storing designs and design representations of
  	electrical or thermal components in a library along with complete functional and simulation models for those
  	components. In this way, a complex component will need to have its functional to physical mapping defined and stored only once.
  	Obviously, an assembly that is physically complex can be considered a component and relevant information stored in a library.
  	The physical interconnect "wiring" may be assigned to electrical, thermal, magnetic, or optical domains with capabilities to apply material classification properties
  	to the "wiring" and to supporting material structures for verification purposes.
  	The packaging conformance options are:




     		Assignment of a delay between two packaged nodes to the component implementing the path in an assembly;



     		Assignment of a packaged node to the component implementing the node in an assembly;



     		Electrotechnical assembly network model;



     		Functional network mapping to interconnect design elements.




4.1.2.6 Communication Protocol physical layers
     	Support is provided to specify low level protocol layers typically associated with physical design. This provides the ability to explicitly specify a source for a requirement
     rather than using an external document approach.




     			Physical layer protocol model.




4.1.2.7 Physical design


     		In the context of this part of ISO 10303 assembly design and interconnect design inherit common characteristics from a more generic physical design level.
     		The physical design level conformance options are:




     			Physical and keepout model shape classification;



     			Physical design model manifold surface shape;



     			Physical interface model.





4.1.2.7 Assembly design


The assembly design provides a similar capability to the functional design, that is hiearchical physical
design is supported.  The model provides the ability for a design organization to substitute various possible alternatives for analysis while maintaining the same physical interface
definition.  It is possible to
model at the semiconductor device, package, substrate, module, black box (multiple modules in one box), drawer, rack, and system level.  Parts of a design may be stored in
a library as a 'macro' and re-used.  Complete designs, including interfaces, may be stored in a library and re-used. Various options
for physical shape are provided to support analysis.  Discrete wire and detailed cable routing is supported. Critical assembly feature to feature relationships  are provided to support verification
that the "as-designed" assembly including interconnect satisfies the physical connectivity definition defined during packaging.





