4.1.2.9 Component data


This part of ISO 10303 provides complete support for all data commonly found in a component data sheet, including functional and physical properties.
The physical properties, component feature classification and terminal and connection area identification are directly supported including various shape models for analysis and Geometric Dimensioning and Tolerancing.
Orientation identification is unambiguously supported with direct support for both three dimensional master models as well as derived two dimensional models.
Direct support for unpackaged (bare) die usage is provided, as well as packaged components.  Support is provided for thermal analysis of complex multi-chip substrates such as MCM.
Component features may be specified in accordance with their function, location and may be grouped. Behavioural models may be assigned to components as well as to terminals, which may be modeled as whole elements or modeled with connection areas.
Connectors are an important component and there are several models provided that may be used depending on the context, ranging from a minimal connector defined to support the physical layer definition
in an electrical protocol to a complete connector definition intended to support three dimensional mockup interconnect traceability.
When this capability is combined with the capability to define CAD footprints for a particular package and fabrication technology, a rather complete library data set is supported.
Cables are often part of an assembly or interconnect and support is provided for the external definition of the functional and physical properties of a cable, including connector positioning if available.
The component data conformance options include the conformance options specified in Clause 4.1.1 as well as the following:






	   			Cable interface model;



	   			Component black box model;



	   			Component footprint definition;



	   			Component functional modifications;



	   			Component package model;



	   			Component package model in a 2D context;



	   			Component package model in a 3D context;



	   			Component package model with corresponding 2D and 3D contexts;



	   			Component physical modifications;



	   			Component white box model for analysis;



	   			Connector model;



	   			Functional specification;



	   			Part feature grouping;



	   			Predefined part feature functional classification;



	   			Product marking;



	   			Test requirement allocation;



	   			Unpackaged semiconductor device interface model.





